Over the eight weeks when Covid-19 hit hard, one typically would have expected, based on the past five years, 81,500 people to have died. In reality, 131,468 did. That means there were around 50,000 excess deaths.
https://t.co/EJAQJtDFzL https://t.co/5KzCIaCH45

@spreadsheetben @harrytlambert @NewStatesman But these are not the areas most at-risk from Covid-19. In the wake of 50,000 excess deaths, it is easy to lose sight of a simple fact: the most vulnerable parts of the UK have not, at least relatively, been badly hit so far.

Read more here: 
https://t.co/EJAQJtDFzL https://t.co/YppVeYra4M

@spreadsheetben 2. Spain made moves to ease lockdown when daily infections were 33% of their peak, France 26%, Germany 18% and Italy 15%.

The current number of new daily infections in the UK is around 39% of peak levels.
https://t.co/KXkhV2hVLb https://t.co/9yfwYoc4LY

@spreadsheetben 4. Easing lockdown should take these local and regional factors into account. Not all parts of the UK peaked at exactly the same time. 

For every local authority in the UK with the pandemic supposedly at bay, there's another with it only just peaking.

https://t.co/KXkhV2hVLb

@spreadsheetben 5. Is the UK easing lockdown too soon? Hard to say, says @spreadsheetben, but for sure, it's a gamble.

